### 4. SETTLE deferral (tool result gating)

After DISPATCH executes tools, the next tick's SETTLE phase drains those results. Each result is pressure-gated — but SETTLE never kills agents directly. Items that don't fit are deferred until headroom recovers:

```typescript
const settlePressure = new ContextPressure(ctx, pressureOpts);
let headroom = settlePressure.headroom;

for (const item of items) {
  const a = agentById.get(item.agentId);
  if (!a || a.status === 'idle') continue;

  if (item.prefillTokens.length > headroom) {
    deferred.push(item);  // retry next tick
    continue;
  }

  prefillPairs.push([a.branch, item.prefillTokens]);
  headroom -= item.prefillTokens.length;
}

return deferred;
```

The `headroom` variable is tracked locally because `cellsUsed` doesn't update until `store.prefill()` at the end of the phase. The local accounting ensures all items are evaluated against the same baseline.

Tool results are the largest KV consumers. A `web_search` result can be 2,000+ tokens. A `fetch_page` result can be 6,000+. SETTLE deferral is the primary backpressure mechanism during active research.

**Staggered exit in parallel orchestration.** In `parallel` orchestration, deferred items stay in `pendingSettled` across ticks. Headroom recovers when a sibling agent reports and its branch is pruned (`pruneOnReturn: true` — default). Next tick, the deferred tool result against the fresh (larger) headroom fits. This is the staggered-exit pattern: one agent's big result is absorbed by another's completion.

**Spine growth in chain orchestration.** In `chain`, each task's findings accumulate on the spine via `ctx.extendSpine` (typically 500–1,500 tokens per task). The spine grows monotonically; later tasks have less starting headroom than earlier ones. Size `hardLimit` and `softLimit` to accommodate the final task's constraints, not the first's.

**DAG orchestration** is a hybrid — dependent tasks inherit extended spine from predecessors; independent siblings stagger like parallel. Pressure behavior follows whichever property dominates at each node.

## Tool anatomy

From `packages/agents/src/Tool.ts`, the base class:

```typescript
abstract class Tool<TArgs = Record<string, unknown>> {
  abstract readonly name: string;
  abstract readonly description: string;
  abstract readonly parameters: JsonSchema;
  abstract execute(args: TArgs, context?: ToolContext): Operation<unknown>;
}
```

| Member | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `name` | Function identifier in tool calls. Must be unique within a toolkit. |
| `description` | Shown to the model in the system prompt. Drives tool selection. |
| `parameters` | JSON Schema describing expected arguments. |
| `execute()` | Generator function that performs the work and returns the result. |
| `probe` | Optional getter returning `string \| null`. When non-null, the pool prefills this text after the tool result settles — nudging the model to reason before the next tool call. Default: `null` (noop). |

The `schema` getter (inherited) auto-generates the OpenAI-compatible function schema from these fields. You never construct the schema manually.

## Configure budget and recovery

Context pressure, time limits, and scratchpad recovery are configured on the policy:

```typescript
const policy = new DefaultAgentPolicy({
  budget: {
    context: { softLimit: 2048 },                            // nudge with 2k cells left
    time: { softLimit: 480_000, hardLimit: 600_000 },        // nudge at 8min, kill at 10min
  },
  recovery: { prompt: REPORT },                              // grammar-constrained extraction
});

const pool = yield* agentPool({
  // ...
  policy,
});
```

Higher `softLimit` means agents are nudged earlier, preserving room for downstream stages. Lower `softLimit` lets agents run longer but risks downstream stages running out of KV.

Rule of thumb: research pools (broad investigation, longer running) get a policy with budget + recovery. Reporter or synthesis pools that only need one `report()` call use the default policy.

## `DefaultAgentPolicy` configuration

```typescript
import { DefaultAgentPolicy } from "@lloyal-labs/lloyal-agents";

const policy = new DefaultAgentPolicy({
  // Tool guards
  minToolCallsBeforeReturn: 2,  // default 2
  extraGuards: [],

  // Search strategy — two-axis explore/exploit (both must agree for explore)
  shouldExplore: { context: 0.4, time: 0.5 },

  // Budget (lifecycle knob — nudge at softLimit, kill at hardLimit)
  budget: {
    context: { softLimit: 1024, hardLimit: 512 },  // KV tokens remaining
    time: { softLimit: 480_000, hardLimit: 600_000 },  // ms since policy creation
  },

  // Recovery extraction for killed agents
  recovery: {
    prompt: { system: "Summarize all findings.", user: "Report your findings." },
    minTokens: 100,      // confabulation guard
    minToolCalls: 2,
  },
});
```

| Option | Default | Effect |
|--------|---------|--------|
| `minToolCallsBeforeReturn` | 2 | Agents with fewer non-terminal tool calls get nudged when trying to report (unless under pressure) |
| `guards` | 3 default guards | Replaces the entire guard array when provided |
| `extraGuards` | `[]` | Appended to default guards |
| `shouldExplore.context` | 0.4 | Min fraction of KV capacity remaining for explore mode |
| `shouldExplore.time` | 0.5 | Max fraction of time soft limit consumed before exploit mode |
| `terminalToolName` | — | Tool name protected from `shouldExit` during generation |
| `budget.context.softLimit` | 1024 | KV tokens remaining that triggers nudge |
| `budget.context.hardLimit` | 512 | KV tokens remaining that triggers kill; reserves recovery budget. Must be >= `nBatch` (enforced at pool startup). |
| `budget.time.softLimit` | — | Milliseconds since policy creation that triggers nudge |
| `budget.time.hardLimit` | — | Milliseconds since policy creation that triggers kill |
| `recovery.prompt` | — | System + user prompt for recovery extraction |
| `recovery.minTokens` | 100 | Skip extraction for agents with fewer tokens |
| `recovery.minToolCalls` | 2 | Skip extraction for agents with fewer tool calls |

## `Branch.create` -- cold start

`Branch.create` allocates a new branch at a given position with its own sampler chain:

```typescript
const branch = Branch.create(ctx, position, params, nBatch, grammar);
```

- **`ctx`** -- `SessionContext` providing access to the KV cache and model.
- **`position`** -- Starting position in the KV cache. For a fresh conversation, this is 0 (cold start). For continuing a conversation, this is the current token count.
- **`params`** -- Sampling parameters (temperature, topP, topK, minP). Controls the sampler chain created for this branch.
- **`nBatch`** -- Per-branch batch size for `prefill()`. Defaults to the context's nBatch. Controls how many tokens are sent per `llama_decode` call during prefill.
- **`grammar`** -- Optional GBNF grammar string. When provided, `sample()` returns only grammar-valid tokens.

A newly created branch has no tokens in its KV cache. Call `prefill()` to decode prompt tokens before generating.

```typescript
// Cold start: create at position 0, prefill system prompt
const root = Branch.create(ctx, 0, { temperature: 0.5 });
const tokens = ctx.tokenizeSync(formattedPrompt);
await root.prefill(tokens);
// root.position is now tokens.length
```

This is the pattern `withSpine` uses internally: create a root at position 0, prefill the shared system prompt, then pass the root to the body for forking.

## The interface

```typescript
interface AgentPolicy {
  onProduced(agent, parsed, pressure, config): ProduceAction;
  onSettleReject(agent, resultTokens, pressure, config): SettleAction;
  shouldExplore?(agent, pressure): boolean;
  shouldExit?(agent, pressure): boolean;
  onRecovery?(agent, pressure): RecoveryAction;
  readonly pressureThresholds?: PressureThresholds;
  resetTick?(): void;
}
```

Five hooks plus a getter, called at different points in the [tick loop](/under-the-hood/concurrency#tick-loop):

| Hook | Phase | When | What it decides |
|------|-------|------|-----------------|
| `shouldExit` | PRODUCE (pre-generate) | Before each agent produces tokens | Kill immediately — no chance to respond |
| `onProduced` | PRODUCE (post-generate) | Agent hit stop token | Tool call, report, nudge, or kill |
| `onSettleReject` | SETTLE stall-break | Deferred tool result with no active siblings | Nudge or drop |
| `shouldExplore` | DISPATCH | Before each tool executes | Explore mode or exploit mode |
| `onRecovery` | Kill + post-loop | For each killed agent without result | Extract findings (with budget) or skip |
| `pressureThresholds` | Pool setup | Once at pool initialization | KV softLimit and hardLimit |

The policy receives the agent's full state — status, tool history, result, token count — plus a live [ContextPressure](/under-the-hood/kv-pressure) snapshot and pool configuration. It returns an action. The pool executes it.

#### "How do I tune budgets and recovery?" — `policy`

The default `DefaultAgentPolicy` is fine to start. You'll customize it when:
- The default time budget (`time: { softLimit: 120_000, hardLimit: 180_000 }`) is too tight for your tool calls.
- You want a custom recovery prompt for `recoverInline` extraction.
- You want extra tool guards (the default has dedup guards for `web_search` / `fetch_page` and a research-before-delegation gate).

```typescript
const policy = new DefaultAgentPolicy({
  budget: {
    context: { softLimit: 2048, hardLimit: 1024 },
    time: { softLimit: 240_000, hardLimit: 360_000 },
  },
  recovery: { prompt: REPORT_PROMPT },
});

yield* agentPool({ orchestrate, tools, policy });
```

## Writing a custom policy

Implement the `AgentPolicy` interface to control any lifecycle decision:

```typescript
import type { AgentPolicy, ProduceAction, SettleAction, RecoveryAction } from "@lloyal-labs/lloyal-agents";
import type { ContextPressure } from "@lloyal-labs/lloyal-agents";

class MyPolicy implements AgentPolicy {
  onProduced(agent, parsed, pressure, config): ProduceAction {
    // Return: tool_call, return, nudge, idle, or free_text_return
  }

  onSettleReject(agent, resultTokens, pressure, config): SettleAction {
    // Return: nudge (with message) or idle
  }

  shouldExplore(agent, pressure): boolean {
    return pressure.percentAvailable > 50;
  }

  shouldExit(agent, pressure): boolean {
    return pressure.critical;
  }

  onRecovery(agent): RecoveryAction {
    if (agent.tokenCount < 100) return { type: 'skip' };
    return { type: 'extract', prompt: { system: '...', user: '...' } };
  }

  get pressureThresholds() {
    return { softLimit: 2048, hardLimit: 256 };
  }
}
```

Pass to any pool via the `policy` option:

```typescript
yield* agentPool({ tasks, tools, systemPrompt, policy: new MyPolicy() });
```

Signatures are narrow by design: `(agent, pressure)`. The policy is a class — time, cost, or other signals live on `this`. The pool passes what it owns (agent + pressure snapshot); the policy combines with its own state.

The policy instance is shared across all agents in a pool. For nested pools (recursive tools), the inner pool receives the same policy instance.

## Context size (nCtx)

`nCtx` is the total KV cache budget in tokens. All agents, spines, tool results, and intermediate branches share this budget.

```typescript
const nCtx = parseInt(process.env.LLAMA_CTX_SIZE || '16384', 10);
const ctx = yield* call(() =>
  createContext({
    modelPath,
    nCtx,
    // ...
  }),
);
```

## Sequence count (nSeqMax)

`nSeqMax` is the maximum number of concurrent branches (sequences) in the KV cache. Each active agent, spine, scratchpad fork, and diverge attempt needs its own sequence.

```typescript
const ctx = yield* call(() =>
  createContext({
    modelPath,
    nCtx,
    nSeqMax: Math.max(AGENT_COUNT, VERIFY_COUNT) * 4 + 3,
    // ...
  }),
);
```

## Configure budget and recovery

Context pressure, time limits, and scratchpad recovery are configured on the policy:

```typescript
const policy = new DefaultAgentPolicy({
  budget: {
    context: { softLimit: 2048 },                            // nudge with 2k cells left
    time: { softLimit: 480_000, hardLimit: 600_000 },        // nudge at 8min, kill at 10min
  },
  recovery: { prompt: REPORT },                              // grammar-constrained extraction
});

const pool = yield* agentPool({
  // ...
  policy,
});
```

Higher `softLimit` means agents are nudged earlier, preserving room for downstream stages. Lower `softLimit` lets agents run longer but risks downstream stages running out of KV.

Rule of thumb: research pools (broad investigation, longer running) get a policy with budget + recovery. Reporter or synthesis pools that only need one `report()` call use the default policy.

### Time budget scope

The `_startTime` is set when the policy is constructed. Since the same policy instance is shared across all nesting levels (outer pool and inner pools spawned by DelegateTool), the time budget is global — "the research has a 10 minute budget" applies to all agents at every depth.

Create separate policy instances for stages with different time constraints:

```typescript
const researchPolicy = new DefaultAgentPolicy({
  budget: { context: { softLimit: 1024 }, time: { softLimit: 480_000, hardLimit: 600_000 } },
  recovery: { prompt: REPORT },
});

// Synthesis doesn't need time limits — use default policy
yield* agentPool({ tasks, systemPrompt, tools, policy: researchPolicy, ... });
```

### You never manually prune branches

```typescript
// Wrong — manual lifecycle management
const branch = parent.forkSync();
try { /* ... */ }
finally { branch.pruneSync(); } // What if you forget?

// How lloyal does it — scope-managed
const branch = parent.forkSync();
yield* ensure(() => {
  if (!branch.disposed) branch.pruneSync();
});
// Registered once. It WILL run. You can't forget.
```

### Reset after SETTLE

When a tool result is prefilled into an agent's branch, the grammar state must be reset. The tool result contains text that the grammar was not tracking -- injecting it without resetting would leave the grammar in an inconsistent state. SETTLE handles this:

```typescript
// After prefill succeeds:
for (const a of settledAgents) {
  a.state = 'generating';
  a.rawOutput = '';
  applyLazyGrammar(a);  // fresh grammar state
}
```

The reset is essential. Without it, the grammar would either reject valid tokens (because its internal parser is misaligned with the branch's actual content) or allow invalid tokens (because the parser was tracking the tool call that already completed). Resetting gives the agent a clean slate: free text generation until the next tool call trigger fires.

