### Recursion discipline

Two checks guard the delegation boundary:

**Research-before-delegation** — a declarative [Tool Guard](/build-a-harness/agents-and-pools#tool-guards) checks the agent's **local** tool history (not lineage). Each agent must have done at least one search AND one fetch/read before it can delegate. This prevents blind relay chains where agents pass questions through without investigating.

**Echo detection** — the delegation tool scores proposed sub-questions against the calling agent's own task via the reranker. If all questions are paraphrases (similarity > 0.8), the delegation is rejected. If any question is novel — a concept discovered during reading — the delegation proceeds. This prevents the degenerate recursion where each level re-delegates the same task verbatim, re-discovering the same content at each depth.

Both checks exist because of Continuous Context. When sub-agents fork from the calling agent's branch, they inherit the parent's full KV — every search result, every fetched page, every token generated. A lineage-based research guard would let children bypass by counting the parent's history. An echo delegation would produce children that search the same queries and find the same results, because the inherited context biases them toward the same investigation path. The local-history guard forces each agent to do its own work. The echo guard forces each delegation to contain novel questions.

Same tools at every level — the **prompt** is the differentiator, not the toolkit:

```
Level 0: Entry agent
         Prompt: "Decompose the question, call research, synthesize, report"
         Tools: [grep, search, read_file, report, research]

Level 1: Research agents (spawned by research tool)
         Prompt: "Grep first, then search, then read, then report"
         Tools: [grep, search, read_file, report, research]

Level 2: Deeper research agents (if a level-1 agent calls research)
         Same prompt. Same tools. Same prescribed process.
```

One toolkit at every level — `DelegateTool` makes the toolkit self-referential by running its own `agentPool()` when called:

```typescript
import { DelegateTool } from '@lloyal-labs/rig';

const baseTools = [...source.tools, reportTool];

const delegate = new DelegateTool({
  name: 'research',
  systemPrompt: RESEARCH_PROMPT,
  poolOpts: { tools: [...baseTools, /* nested delegate added below */], terminal: reportTool },
});
// Note: for unbounded depth, share a single DelegateTool reference so its
// poolOpts.tools list includes itself — the pattern compares to the
// classic Y-combinator self-reference.

const pool = yield* agentPool({
  orchestrate: parallel(
    questions.map(q => ({ content: q, systemPrompt: RESEARCH_PROMPT })),
  ),
  tools: [...baseTools, delegate],
  terminal: reportTool,
});
```

## `produce` / `commit` -- the generation protocol

Generation separates sampling from state advancement:

**`produce()` / `produceSync()`** -- Sample the next token from the branch's logits snapshot. Returns `{ token, text, isStop }`. Does NOT write to KV. Does NOT advance position. The branch is unchanged after produce -- you can inspect the result before deciding to commit.

**`commit(token)`** -- Accept the token into the sampler's repeat-penalty window, decode it into KV (writing one cell), and capture new logits. Advances position by 1. After commit, the branch is ready for the next `produce()`.

```typescript
// Manual produce/commit loop
while (true) {
  const { token, text, isStop } = branch.produceSync();
  if (isStop) break;
  await branch.commit(token);
  process.stdout.write(text);
}
```

The agent pool uses this protocol in its tick loop: PRODUCE calls `produceSync()` on all active agents, collecting tokens. COMMIT batch-decodes all produced tokens in a single `store.commit(entries)` call.

### Async iterator

For simpler cases, Branch provides an async iterator with commit-before-yield semantics:

```typescript
for await (const { token, text } of branch) {
  process.stdout.write(text);
}
```

Every yielded token is already committed -- written to KV and accepted into the sampler. Breaking out of the loop is clean. `useAgent()` uses this internally.

## The harness

```typescript daily-digest.ts
import { main, call } from "effection";
import { createContext } from "@lloyal-labs/lloyal.node";
import {
  initAgents, agentPool, chain, Tool, RerankerCtx,
} from "@lloyal-labs/lloyal-agents";
import type { JsonSchema, Operation } from "@lloyal-labs/lloyal-agents";
import {
  createAppRegistry,
  createInMemoryConfigStore,
  reportTool,
} from "@lloyal-labs/rig";
import { createReranker } from "@lloyal-labs/rig/node";
import { createWebApp } from "@lloyal-labs/web-app";

// ── Mailgun delivery tool — wraps the v3 Messages API ──────────
class MailgunTool extends Tool<{ subject: string; html: string; to: string }> {
  readonly name = "send_email";
  readonly description = "Send an HTML email via Mailgun. Use this once the digest is fully drafted.";
  readonly parameters: JsonSchema = {
    type: "object",
    properties: {
      subject: { type: "string", description: "Email subject line" },
      html:    { type: "string", description: "Email body, HTML" },
      to:      { type: "string", description: "Recipient address" },
    },
    required: ["subject", "html", "to"],
  };

  *execute(args: { subject: string; html: string; to: string }): Operation<unknown> {
    const apiKey = process.env.MAILGUN_API_KEY!;
    const domain = process.env.MAILGUN_DOMAIN!;
    const auth = Buffer.from(`api:${apiKey}`).toString("base64");
    const result: unknown = yield* call(() =>
      fetch(`https://api.mailgun.net/v3/${domain}/messages`, {
        method: "POST",
        headers: {
          "Authorization": `Basic ${auth}`,
          "Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded",
        },
        body: new URLSearchParams({
          from: `Daily Digest <digest@${domain}>`,
          to: args.to,
          subject: args.subject,
          html: args.html,
        }).toString(),
      }).then(r => r.json()),
    );
    return result;  // { id, message: 'Queued. Thank you.' } on success
  }
}

const TOPIC = process.argv[3] || "AI safety news this week";
const RECIPIENT = process.env.DIGEST_TO || "me@example.com";
const TODAY = new Date().toISOString().slice(0, 10);

const RESEARCH_PROMPT = `You are a researcher. Use web_search to surface 3-5 stories on the topic, then fetch_page on the highest-signal results to extract details. Anchor queries on the current year. When done, call report() with a concise list — each story: title, source URL, 2-sentence summary, key claim.`;

const DIGEST_PROMPT = `Read the research turn above. Draft a daily digest in HTML:
  <h2>headline summarizing the day in one line</h2>
  <ol> for each story: <li><b>title</b> (<a href="url">source</a>) — 2-3 sentence summary, then bold key claim.</li>
  <p><i>Watching:</i> one-line forward look.</p>
Once the digest HTML is ready, call send_email() with subject "Daily Digest — ${TODAY}", html=<your draft>, to="${RECIPIENT}". Then call report() with "sent: <message_id>".`;

await main(function* () {
  // 1. Load model + reranker
  const ctx = yield* call(() => createContext({
    modelPath: process.argv[2] || "model.gguf",
    nCtx: 32768,
    nSeqMax: 4,
    typeK: "q4_0",
    typeV: "q4_0",
  }));
  const reranker = yield* createReranker(
    process.env.RERANKER_PATH || "reranker.gguf",
    { nCtx: 4096, nSeqMax: 1 },
  );

  yield* initAgents(ctx);

  // 2. Wire an App — its Source + Tools + skill template are
  //    auto-wired into the agent runtime by the registry.
  yield* RerankerCtx.set(reranker);
  const configStore = createInMemoryConfigStore();
  yield* configStore.set("web", { tavilyKey: process.env.TAVILY_API_KEY });
  const registry = yield* createAppRegistry({ configStore });
  const web = yield* registry.enable(createWebApp);

  // 3. Two-step chain — research, then synth-and-deliver
  const pool = yield* agentPool({
    orchestrate: chain(
      [
        { content: `Topic: ${TOPIC}`,    systemPrompt: RESEARCH_PROMPT },
        { content: `Compose and send.`,  systemPrompt: DIGEST_PROMPT },
      ],
      (spec, i) => ({
        task: { ...spec, seed: 100 + i },
        userContent: i === 0
          ? `Step 1: research "${TOPIC}"`
          : `Step 2: compose digest, send via Mailgun`,
      }),
    ),
    tools: [...web.tools, new MailgunTool(), reportTool],
    terminal: reportTool,
    maxTurns: 10,
  });

  pool.agents.forEach((a, i) => {
    console.log(`\n=== step ${i + 1} ===`);
    console.log(a.result || "(no result)");
  });
});
```

```bash
npx tsx daily-digest.ts ./models/Qwen3-4B-Instruct-Q4_K_M.gguf "AI safety news this week"
```

Open your inbox. The digest's there.

### Where to put the spine: harness `withSpine` vs `agentPool({ systemPrompt })`

Spine extensions write to the pool's `spineRoot`. Two configurations decide which branch that is:

- **`agentPool` invoked WITHOUT `systemPrompt`** (the common case for chains that need cross-pool spine persistence). `spineRoot = warmParent` — the root the harness passed in via `parent:`. The harness's outer `withSpine` owns this root for its full scope, so extensions persist past pool exit and a post-pool `useAgent({ parent: querySpine })` forks the spine and attends to all chain extensions.
- **`agentPool` invoked WITH `systemPrompt`** (shared-mode). `agentPool` internally creates a *nested* `withSpine` whose root carries the catalog (the protocol entries + tool schemas). `spineRoot = inner spine`. Extensions write to that inner spine, which gets pruned at `agentPool` exit. A post-pool `useAgent({ parent: querySpine })` would fork the OUTER querySpine and find an empty branch — chain extensions disappeared with the inner spine.

Two patterns both work; pick by where the synth runs:

```typescript
// Pattern A: synth as a DAG node INSIDE the pool (compare's pattern)
yield* withSpine({ parent: session.trunk }, function*(querySpine) {
  return yield* agentPool({
    orchestrate: dag(nodes),    // research → compare → synth as nodes
    systemPrompt: catalog,  // shared-mode is fine: synth's branch
                                // forks the inner spineRoot
    parent: querySpine,
    tools, terminal: reportTool,
  });
});

// Pattern B: synth as a separate useAgent AFTER the pool
yield* withSpine(
  {
    parent: session.trunk,
    systemPrompt: catalog,      // ← protocol catalog on harness root
    tools,  // ← so spine extensions land here
  },
  function*(querySpine) {
    yield* agentPool({
      orchestrate: chain(tasks),
      // NO systemPrompt — non-shared mode, spineRoot = querySpine
      parent: querySpine,
      tools, terminal: reportTool,
    });
    // synth forks querySpine and sees all chain extensions via attention
    return yield* useAgent({ parent: querySpine, /* ... */ });
  },
);
```

See [Mixed-role pools](/under-the-hood/mixed-role-pools) for the prompt convention for mixed-role pools and [Concurrency](/under-the-hood/concurrency#spinefmt--shared-mode) for the `SpineFmt` context that drives shared-mode behavior.

### The grant store

```ts
export interface GrantStore {
  has(toolName: string): Operation<boolean>;
  grant(toolName: string): Operation<void>;
  revoke(toolName: string): Operation<void>;
  granted(): Operation<readonly string[]>;
}
```

A `GrantStore` lives on `GrantStoreCtx`, set by the harness at boot. Semantics from `agents/src/grant-store.ts`:

- **Binary per tool.** A grant is keyed by tool name; either the session holds it or it doesn't. No scopes, no expiry in the base protocol — richer policies are a harness concern.
- **Fail-closed.** With no grant store on `GrantStoreCtx`, no grants exist: every protected tool is denied. Open (non-protected) tools are unaffected.
- **Acquired via consent**, never via the model. The model triggers the call; the runtime holds the grant; the tool's `execute` uses the underlying secret. The credential never enters the model's context.

## The `protected` bit

**Read tools (the default, `protected: false` or unset)** are open: any agent in the pool may call them. Retrieval, file reads, web fetches — anything that *gathers* information rather than mutating state.

**Protected tools (`protected: true`)** are gated at DISPATCH by `authGuard` against a session-held grant. The model sees the tool in the schema and can emit a call; the framework denies the call if no grant exists and emits a `tool:authReject` event:

```ts
export class SendEmailTool extends Tool<{ to: string; subject: string; body: string }> {
  readonly name = "send_email";
  readonly protected = true;            // ← write/sensitive action
  readonly description = "Send an email via the user's connected account.";
  readonly parameters = /* ... */;

  *execute(args, ctx): Operation<unknown> {
    // Runs only if the session holds a grant for "send_email".
    return yield* call(() => this.smtp.send(args));
  }
}
```

The credential itself never enters the model's context. The session holds the grant; the tool body holds the secret; the model only triggers. [App security](/build-an-app/app-security) covers the threat model, grant acquisition flows, and what happens when grants are revoked mid-session.

<Note>
Open-by-default isn't a permission downgrade — it's a recognition that *which tools an agent can call* is already gated at the spine layer: the catalog only lists enabled Apps' tools, and every per-spawn message is prefixed with `Apply the **<protocol>** protocol.` so the model knows the discipline. `protected` is the orthogonal gate for *consequential* actions, not the gate for routing.
</Note>

